{
  "answer": "**The cannibalistic Mermedonians (or people of Mermedonia) are first described shortly after the poem's prologue on the apostles, in the context of introducing Matthew's missionary journey.**[^1]\n\nThis passage explicitly depicts their land as one where foreigners are slaughtered and eaten as a customary \"foul, grim feast\":\n\n> Fate had assigned him that far-off country,  \n> the grim land of **Mermedonia**, a place of dread,  \n> where no guest could journey for gold or for love,  \n> nor find any welcome in that hateful nation.  \n> That whole land was stained, its cities of men  \n> soaked with the slaughter of strangers who came there.  \n> It was the custom of that cursed tribe  \n> that any foreigner who fared to their shores  \n> they **fed upon for food**, a **foul, grim feast**.[^1]\n\nSubsequent references (e.g., as the \"land of the man-eaters\") build on this initial portrayal.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, ch. 1 ([paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-f6e450)).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, ch. 1 ([paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-4d1e78)).",
